lenges include developing a model architecture that can handle the unique characteristics of UI screens, creating comprehensive datasets for training and evaluation, and establishing a benchmark to evaluate models on multiple dimensions of UI screen understanding. Naive approaches may fail due to the specialized nature of UI screens and the need for a tailored solution.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious models have been primarily designed for natural images and do not fully address the specific challenges of UI screens. The lack of specialized datasets and benchmarks has hindered progress in this area. Additionally, the need for a tailored model architecture that can handle the unique characteristics of UI screens has not been fully recognized.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach includes developing a specialized model architecture that can handle the unique challenges of UI screens, creating a comprehensive dataset of UI screens with annotations for referring and grounding tasks, and establishing a benchmark to evaluate models on multiple dimensions of UI screen understanding. The expected outcomes include a more efficient and effective LVLM for mobile UIs, demonstrated through improved performance on the benchmark and practical applications in areas such as accessibility and app testing."}

